Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Promotors regulate transcription by being located upstream of the DNA strand, and provide an initial binding site for the RNA polymerase to bind and then go out to transcribe the DNA until it hits the stop codon.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Transcription differs in eukaryotes from prokaryotes because there are several more factors that eukaryotes have to meet in order to the RNA polymerase to even bind to the promotor region. In prokaryotes however the polymerase needs to be identified by the sigma factor and then it binds,
explainConcepts[SQ003] The genetic code has a 3 base codons that have been transcribed from DNA into MRNA. When this happens the MRNA which consists of these bases it is then translated into proteins because each amino acid is coded to a three base codon.
phenomenonA Transcription is regulated by the promoter.
phenomenonA[comment] Transcription being regulated by the promotor leads to the human body having control over gene expression and without it there is a decreased amount of variability.
phenomenonB The genetic code is the Rosetta stone that translates between mRNA and proteins, 3 bases at a time.
phenomenonB[comment] Without this genetic code the body could not code for proteins which are the basis of many necessary human functions. Even slight frameshift can lead to huge disruptions in the human body and leads to many different diseases.

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] Transcription is regulated by the promoter because it is where the RNA polymerase binds to it and then after that the whole process for transcription can be started.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] Transcription is different in eukaryotes becasause it is much more complicated. There are several more factors including various transcription factors having to bind to the promotor in order to bind for transcription to start rather than one like in prokaryotes.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] When protein codes 3 bases at a time it allows for individual amino acids to be produced and specific proteins for different purposes to be produced. The rosetta stone aspect about it is that it the genetic code can be rearranged in multiple ways to create different proteins.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] The central dogma states that genetic information is stored in DNA, then copied to mRNA during transcription and then made to a protein during translation. Transcriptions starts in the promoter region and goes to the gene start and stop codons until the RNA polymerase is taken off the DNA strand.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] A promoter initiates the process of transcription for genes. Prokaryotes and Eukaryotes have different promoters involved in transcription. The promoter in Eukaryotes is the TATA box.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Transcription in prokaryotes takes place in the cytoplasm, while transcription in Eukaryotes takes place in the nucleus. Once again, the promoters are also different in prokaryotes and eukaryotes. The number of RNA polymerases also differs; eukaryotes have three and prokaryotes have only one.
explainConcepts[SQ003] The genetic code consists of linear triplet codes that convert nucleates to amino acids so that RNA can be translated to proteins. The genetic code is unambiguous, degenerate, and non overlapping.
phenomenonA The genetic code is the Rosetta stone that translates between mRNA and proteins, 3 bases at a time.
phenomenonA[comment] The genetic code is almost completely universal, meaning all cell types and viruses use the same coding; this is important for studying microbes and the fundamentals of microbiology.
phenomenonB Transcription in eukaryotes differs in fundamental ways from transcription in prokaryotes.
phenomenonB[comment] Differences between transcription in prokaryotes and eukaryotes can be useful for the development of medicines. A medicine that targets and interrupts transcriptional aspects of prokaryotes but do not interfere with eukaryotic transcription could be used to treat infections, such as a bacterial infection.
groupTime456 974.91

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] I understand that a promoter initiates transcription and differs between prokaryotic and eukaryotic cells. I understand that promoters are located near the start site of transcription. I do not understand the response mechanism of promoters that allow them to initiate transcription.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I understand that transcription takes place in the nucleus in Eukaryotes; prokaryotes do not have nuclei so transcription takes place in the cytoplasm. I know that Eukaryotes need transcription factors in order to initiate transcription, but prokaryotes do not.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] The genetic code consists of the a sequence ribonucleotide triplets that code for only one amino acid, but one amino acid may be specified by more than one triplet. I understand that the codons in the genetic code are in a collinear sequence, and the sequence does not overlap.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] The central dogma (DNA->RNA->proteins) begins with transcription. DNA serves as a template for RNA synthesis; the non-coding stand is copied, and synthesis takes place from 5' to 3'. The synthesized mRNA strand is identical to the coding strand, except that it has U's instead of T's.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] The promoter is the sequence that is at the beginning of the coding sequence. If the promoted is activated, then the following sequence can be transcribed and ultimately translated, but if the promoter is not activated, then the sequence will not be coded and the gene will not be expressed.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Transcription in eukaryotes occurs with multiple promoters and genes being expressed at once, but in prokaryotes, there is only one origin of replication per DNA molecule. Also, only one replication bubble forms in prokaryotic replication.
explainConcepts[SQ003] mRNA is broken into codons, and then these codons are "read" by tRNAs that assign a specific amino acid to the specific codon. The Rosetta stone analogy means that this codon sequence can be used to entirely translate and form a functional protein from the mRNA sequence without any ambiguity or inconsistencies.
phenomenonA The genetic code is the Rosetta stone that translates between mRNA and proteins, 3 bases at a time.
phenomenonA[comment] UCU UAU UGU as an mRNA sequence codes for the amino acids Serine, Tyrosine, and Cysteine, respectively.
phenomenonB The genetic code is the Rosetta stone that translates between mRNA and proteins, 3 bases at a time.
phenomenonB[comment] CCU CAU CGU as an mRNA sequence codes for the amino acids Proline, Histidine, and Arginine, respectively.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] a promoter is a region of DNA that initiates transcription of a particular gene. Promoters are located near the transcription start sites of genes, on the same strand and upstream on the DNA
explainConcepts[SQ002] Transcription is achieved by three different types of RNA polymerase (RNA pol I-III). These polymerases differ in the number and type of subunits they contain, as well as the class of RNAs they transcribeIn bacteria, all transcription is performed by a single type of RNA polymerase. This polymerase contains four catalytic subunits and a single regulatory subunit.
explainConcepts[SQ003] The genetic code is the set of rules by which information encoded within genetic material (DNA or mRNA sequences) is translated into proteins by living cells
phenomenonA Transcription in eukaryotes differs in fundamental ways from transcription in prokaryotes.
phenomenonA[comment] Initiation factors are not needed in prokaryotes but in eukaryotes they need a transcription factor to recognize the TATA box to begin transcription.
phenomenonB The genetic code is the Rosetta stone that translates between mRNA and proteins, 3 bases at a time.
phenomenonB[comment] While the genetic code determines the protein sequence for a given coding region, other genomic regions can influence when and where these proteins are produced.
groupTime456 549.95

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] For the transcription to take place, the enzyme that synthesizes RNA, known as RNA polymerase, must attach to the DNA near a gene. Promoters contain specific DNA sequences such as response elements that provide a secure initial binding site for RNA polymerase and for proteins called transcription factors that recruit RNA polymerase. These transcription factors have specific activator or repressor sequences of corresponding nucleotides that attach to specific promoters and regulate gene expression.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] Although both prokaryotes and eukaryotes modify tRNA and rRNA, eukaryotes very extensively process nRNA destined to become mRNA. Primary transcripts (pre-mRNA molecules), the products of RNA polymerase action, acquire a cap at their 5′ ends and a poly(A) tail at their 3′ ends. Most importantly, nearly all mRNA precursors in higher eukaryotes are spliced
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] The code defines how sequences of these nucleotide triplets, called codons, specify which amino acid will be added next during protein synthesis. With some exceptions a three-nucleotide codon in a nucleic acid sequence specifies a single amino acid.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] The ribosomes are the sites of protein synthesis. the mRNA strand attaches to a ribosome. tRNA molecules transport specific amino acids to the ribosome. each mRNA codon codes for a specific amino acid.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] The promotor must bind to the DNA before transcription can occur. It must open the strand and allow other proteins to attach. This makes it the simplest way for evolution to limit the amount of transcription occurring in the cell or to increase the amount as needed.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Transcription in prokaryotes is different from eukaryotes because prokaryotes have a simple ring of DNA that is not intertwined with proteins. The polymerases and a few other proteins must simply attach to the chain and reproduce it. There is also significantly less DNA in a prokaryote than a eukaryote. The opposite is true for eukaryotes. They have histone proteins and a large genome.
explainConcepts[SQ003] The genetic code is the same for almost all organisms. The mRNA is translated to proteins through the three bases read at the ribosome. This process requires tRNA to carry the amino acids and the ribosome to attach them together.
phenomenonA Transcription is regulated by the promoter.
phenomenonA[comment] If I am not mistaken, this is part of the reason for lactose intolerance. I believe it is something having to do with the promotor for lactase being absent or malfunctioning in some way. This is relevant to me as I am lactose intolerant for large amounts of it.
phenomenonB The genetic code is the Rosetta stone that translates between mRNA and proteins, 3 bases at a time.
phenomenonB[comment] This is how human genes are placed in prokaryotic genomes to produce things like insulin, completely identical to the protein produced in humans.

groupTime455 26.44

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] The promoter region is very important in the process of transcription. The TATA and CAT boxes are what DNA polymerase bind to. For both prokaryotes and eukaaryotes, the promotor region is very important. Without it, transcription would never be able to happen.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Prokaryotes do not have introns, while eukaryotes have introns. This means that there is more gene regulation in eukaryotes than prokaryotes. Both prokaryotes and eukaryotes have promoter regions, consisting of the TATA and CAT box, but in eukaryotes, DNA polymerase must have extra help to bind to the promoter region. Prokaryotic DNA polymerase can simply attach and begin the process of transcription. Eukaryotic DNA must undergo chromatin remodeling, while prokaryotes do not have to.
explainConcepts[SQ003] This is a major part of transcription and translation. The genetic code is what tells the ribosome which amino acid to put in the protein chain. Every three bases translates into an amino acid. For example, AUG is the three base sequence that codes for Methionine, which is the very important start codon. Without this codon, the process of translation does not ever occur, and if it does not happen, proteins are never made.
phenomenonA Transcription in eukaryotes differs in fundamental ways from transcription in prokaryotes.
phenomenonA[comment] Eukaryotic transcription is much more complex than prokaryotic transcription, which helps to conclude that eukaryotes are much more complex. There is much more gene regulation in eukaryotes, which allows for greater success and a more complex form.
phenomenonB Transcription is regulated by the promoter.
phenomenonB[comment] If transcription is not regulated by the promoter, it will never occur, thus DNA will never be copied and no new proteins will be made from that particular strand of DNA.

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] The promoter region is very important in the process of transcription. The TATA and CAT boxes are what DNA polymerase bind to. For both prokaryotes and eukaaryotes, the promotor region is very important. Without it, transcription would never be able to happen.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] Prokaryotes do not have introns, while eukaryotes have introns. This means that there is more gene regulation in eukaryotes than prokaryotes. Both prokaryotes and eukaryotes have promoter regions, consisting of the TATA and CAT box, but in eukaryotes, DNA polymerase must have extra help to bind to the promoter region. Prokaryotic DNA polymerase can simply attach and begin the process of transcription. Eukaryotic DNA must undergo chromatin remodeling, while prokaryotes do not have to.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] This is a major part of transcription and translation. The genetic code is what tells the ribosome which amino acid to put in the protein chain. Every three bases translates into an amino acid. For example, AUG is the three base sequence that codes for Methionine, which is the very important start codon. Without this codon, the process of translation does not ever occur, and if it does not happen, proteins are never made.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] The central dogma of biology is that genetic material is stored in DNA, transformed into RNA during transcription, and further transformed into protein during translation. Transcriptions starts in the promoter region and proceeds past the gene start and stop codons until RNA polymerase is removed from the DNA strand.

explainConcepts[SQ003] The reading frame of the genetic code 3 bases at a time is called a codon. Each codon codes for a specific amino acid. There are 20 different amino acids coded for by the 64 different codon combinations of RNA using the bases A, U, G, and C.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] The promoter region is an area of the DNA where the polymerase will bind to begin transcription, therefore if something is wrong with this area, transcription will be affected.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Transcription in eukaryotes is a simpler process that is generally the same as in eukaryotes, except eukaryotes have extra steps afterwards since the mRNA must be moved out of the nucleus to the ribosomes for translation to start. Prokaryotes do not have this problem, and transcription and translation can occur simultaneously. Prokaryotes have a TATA box, CAT box, and Shine-Delgarno sequence, and transcription starts directly after the promoter region, while eukaryotes have dozens of proteins involved as enhancers and silencers, and require transcription factors as well as RNA Pol1,2, and 3. Eukaryotes have a CAAT box and the Goldberg-Hogness box instead of a TATA box. Also there are many post-transcriptional events that happen in eukaryotic cells.
explainConcepts[SQ003] The genetic code is the relation between three base pairs (a codon) and a corresponding amino acid. The code allows tRNA to place the correct amino acid in the growing polypeptide chain in the right place and therefore allow mRNA to transfer its information into the form of a protein.

groupTime455 22.94

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] A promoter is a sequence of nucleotide bases in the genome that serve as a signal and binding site for RNA polymerase. This is important because without these promoter regions, RNA polymerase will not be able to recognize the gene it is supposed to transcribe, and the gene will not be transcribed. The promoter sequence is commonly called the TATA box, and this region is upstream of the gene to be transcribed itself. Mutations in the promoter sequences result in the inability of RNA polymerase to function, therefore the gene is non-functional because it cannot enter the “central dogma” flow to become a polypeptide.
explainConcepts[SQ002] There are 5 major ways that transcription differs in eukaryotes and prokaryotes. The first difference is that, unlike prokaryotes that have a circular genome, eukaryotes have linear DNA. This creates an issue at the end of the strand that is solved via the mechanisms of telomerases. The second difference is that eukaryotic transcription is much slower (25 x), but this slow speed is made up for by multiple origins of replication. The third difference is that eukaryotes have nucleosomes, which are structures of histone proteins that clump together and compact the DNA in the strand (also turn off genes in clumped region). The fourth difference is that eukaryotes use two different polymerases to copy the leading and lagging strands (versus only one polymerase in prokaryotes). The fifth difference is found during initiation of transcription in that in eukaryotes, there is primer RNA that is then converted in DNA and in prokaryotes there is just an RNA primer.
explainConcepts[SQ003] The nucleotides bases that make up the mRNA are read via open reading frames by the ribosome in the cytoplasm. Thanks to tRNA, amino acid residues are added to a growing polypeptide chain one at a time as the tRNA delivers the specific amino acid according to the anticodon sequence on the opposite end of the tRNA. The three base groupings are called codons, and every combination of the four nucleotide bases codes for an amino acid, a start codon (AUG), or one of the three stop codons (UGA, UAA, UGG).
phenomenonA Transcription in eukaryotes differs in fundamental ways from transcription in prokaryotes.
phenomenonA[comment] The evolutionary benefits and expanded possibilities that result from various mechanisms used by eukaryotes has now been traced back and suggested to all be from RNA.
phenomenonB Transcription is regulated by the promoter.
phenomenonB[comment] Mutations in the promoter region of DNA have been implicated in a variety of diseases, including asthma. Mutations in the promoter affect the first step of the central dogma (DNA → RNA), because the DNA cannot be transcribed properly to begin the pathway to becoming a protein.

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] I understand that the process of transcription, that is, making RNA from the DNA template, requires a promoter. This promoter helps regulate transcription, which is important because different cells in the body have different needs at different times. By having promoter regions, RNA polymerase (the enzyme that creates the RNA off the DNA template) can selectively transcribe only the sequences of genes that the cell needs at that given time. Regulation of transcription via promoter regions is just one of many of the regulation mechanisms cells have to control the production of various gene products. I understand that the promoter region we have covered is the TATA box.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I understand that there are five main differences in transcription between eukaryotes and prokaryotes. First, transcription in eukaryotes is much slower, and this handicap is made up for in that eukaryotes have multiple origins of replication (unlike prokaryotes that only have one origin of replication). Second, eukaryotic DNA is linear, and to keep all of the genes and crucial genetic information from slowly being chewed away at the ends of the chromosomes, eukaryotic chromosomes have telomerase at the ends. Third, eukaryotes use two different RNA polymerases instead of just the one RNA polymerase present in prokaryotic cells. Fourth, eukaryotic DNA is packaged into nucleosomes, which must be removed in order to transcribe genes. Lastly, in eukaryotes the primer is RNA then DNA, and in prokaryotes it is just a RNA primer.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand that the genetic code is the Rosetta stone, in that there are three different “languages” or versions of the same code that result from our specific sequences of DNA. Going along with the central dogma, DNA (first language) is first transcribed to RNA (second language), then in the cytoplasm of the cells, RNA is translated into polypeptides chains (third language) that are further processed in various ways to result in functioning proteins in the cell. This code is passed on in three bases groupings called codons. Ribosomes in the cytoplasm read the mRNA strands three base pairs at a time (open-reading frame), and tRNA carries the appropriate amino acid to the ribosome to be added to the growing polypeptide chain. These codons are degenerate, in that one amino acid can be represented by more than one codon (three base grouping) sequence.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I understand that transcription is the first step in the central dogma of biology. The central dogma of biology has three stages with two processes involved. These stages and processes are, first, that DNA is transcribed into RNA (through the process of transcription). Second, RNA is translated via ribosomes in the cytoplasm of the cell into polypeptide chains (proteins) via the process of translation. In summary, the three “stages” are DNA → RNA → protein, and the processes that accomplish these conversions are transcription then translation.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Transcription is the process of converting the DNA code to mRNA, tRNA, or rRNA. mRNA is used to then translate the code into an amino acid sequence, or polypeptide. To initiate transcription in prokaryotes, there is a TATA box upstream along with a CAT box. RNA Polymerase and the sigma factor bind to this TATA box to initiate transcription. In eukaryotes, transcription begins when the TBP, or TATA Binding Protein, and the Transcription factor II-D bind to the TATA box and form a complex for RNA Polymerase to come in. These promoters are upstream from the start codon, so they copy more information than is needed, which helps maintain the entire gene.
explainConcepts[SQ002] In eukaryotes, transcription begins by TBP and TF II-D binding to the TATA box while prokaryotes bind RNA Polymerase and sigma factor to the TATA box for initiation. Eukaryotic transcription occurs in the nucleus instead of the cytoplasm, so it is matured by capping the 5 prime end with 7-methylguanosine, splicing the noncoding introns out, and adding a poly-A tail to the other end of the mRNA. Prokaryotic transcription occurs in the cytoplasm, so it immediately binds to a ribosome to start translation as it is being transcribed.
explainConcepts[SQ003] The genetic code includes 64 codons that code for the 20 different amino acids. The genetic code is linear, commaless, ordered, nearly universal, and degenerate in that several codons can code for one amino acid. The codons of the genetic code match with an anticodon on tRNA that carries a particular amino acid during translation, which is how the bases attract a specific amino acid.
phenomenonA The genetic code is the Rosetta stone that translates between mRNA and proteins, 3 bases at a time.
phenomenonA[comment] I am intersted in the Wobble Hypothesis. I had never heard of this hypothesis before, and I find it interesting how the third amino acid in the codon can allow for a nonpairing amino acid on the anticodon to match with it. This wobble shows why it is important that the genetic code is degenerate.
phenomenonB Transcription in eukaryotes differs in fundamental ways from transcription in prokaryotes.
phenomenonB[comment] I find it interesting that the different structures of the prokaryotic and eukaryotic DNA determine how complex transcription must be. For example, prokaryotic transcription occurs in the cytoplasm so translation can be happening as the mRNA is being formed. Eukaryotic transcription occurs in the nucleus, so the pre-mRNA must be capped, spliced, and given a tail before it can leave the nucleus to undergo translation.

groupTime455 20.61

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Promoters are regions of DNA that promote transcription, transcription begins with the binding of RNA polymerase to the promoter in DNA.
explainConcepts[SQ002] After the first bond is synthesized, the RNA polymerase must clear the promoter. During this time there is a tendency to release the RNA transcript and produce truncated transcripts. This is called abortive initiation and is common for both eukaryotes and prokaryotes. In prokaryotes, abortive initiation continues to occur until an RNA product of a threshold length of approximately 10 nucleotides is synthesized, at which point promoter escape occurs and a transcription elongation complex is formed. The σ factor is released according to a stochastic model. Mechanistically, promoter escape occurs through a scrunching mechanism, where the energy built up by DNA scrunching provides the energy needed to break interactions between RNA polymerase holoenzyme and the promoter. In eukaryotes, after several rounds of 10nt abortive initiation, promoter clearance coincides with the TFIIH's phosphorylation of serine 5 on the carboxy terminal domain of RNAP II, leading to the recruitment of capping enzyme . The exact mechanism of how CE induces promoter clearance in eukaryotes is not yet known.
explainConcepts[SQ003] A codon is defined by the initial nucleotide from which translation starts. For example, the string GGGAAACCC, if read from the first position, contains the codons GGG, AAA, and CCC; and, if read from the second position, it contains the codons GGA and AAC; if read starting from the third position, GAA and ACC. Every sequence can, thus, be read in three reading frames, each of which will produce a different amino acid sequence . With double-stranded DNA, there are six possible reading frames, three in the forward orientation on one strand and three reverse on the opposite strand. The actual frame in which a protein sequence is translated is defined by a start codon, usually the first AUG codon in the mRNA sequence.
phenomenonA Transcription is regulated by the promoter.
phenomenonA[comment] Promoters are regions of DNA that promote transcription, transcription begins with the binding of RNA polymerase to the promoter in DNA.
phenomenonB Transcription in eukaryotes differs in fundamental ways from transcription in prokaryotes.
phenomenonB[comment] After the first bond is synthesized, the RNA polymerase must clear the promoter. knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Transcription is the process by which the information contained in a section of DNA is replicated in the form of a newly assembled piece of messenger RNA (mRNA). Processing includes the addition of a 5' cap and a poly-A tail to the pre-mRNA chain, followed by splicing. Alternative splicing occurs when appropriate, increasing the diversity of the proteins that any single mRNA can produce. The product of the entire transcription process that began with the production of the pre-mRNA chain, is a mature mRNA chain.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] A promoter sequence allows RNA polymerase to bind to it and bring along other factors. In prokaryotes, this action is a little different since it requires a holoenzyme (composed of 2 alpha, a beta, beta prime, omega, and a specific sigma subunit). The sigma subunit is a specific subunit that varies from sequence to sequence, but all the other subunits listed compose the core enzyme which can continue adding RNA nucleotides or ribonucleotides once the sigma subunit has facilitated binding to the promoter region and has added a few bases before it leaves. I'm eukaryotes, different RNA Polymerases have different jobs or functions associated with them. RNA Polymerase 2 which is used to create mRNA requires Transcription Factors such as TFIID and TBD (TATA binding proteins) to first attach to the promoter region. Once the RNA Polymerase II is attached to the pre-initiation complex, transcription can begin once the tail of Polymerase has been phosphorylated by the TFIID protein. In addition, there are suppressors and enhancers that can also regulate the transcription process by determining if there is a change in environment via signals that may require an increase of a decrease in certain proteins ( therefore, more or less mRNA transcripts to allow for the increase or decrease in protein requirement).
explainConcepts[SQ002] Eukaryotic transcription varies highly from prokaryotic transcription in specific and fundamental ways. For instance, transcription occurs in the nucleus in a eukaryotic cell, unlike prokaryotes, before it can be transmitted out the nuclear pore into the cytoplasm for translation. Therefore, transcription and translation is not simultaneous within an Eykaryotic cell. Furthermore since eukaryotic DNA has his tone proteins associated with it to create nucleosomes ("beads on a string complex"), the histone proteins must be removed temporarily which also requires other specific mechanisms. In addition, the initiation of transcription varies between eukaryotes and prokaryotes, wherein, eukaryotes require TFIID, TBP, and RNA Polymerase II whereas, prokaryotes require a holoenzyme formation at the promoter.
explainConcepts[SQ003] This statement is a synopsis of the central dogma which claims that a DNA strand is used as a template to create RNA (mRNA, tRNA, and rRNA) in which each play a role in the process of protein formation. These two steps discusses are transcription and translation, respectively. The DNA which is known as the genetic code, is known to be read in codons or 3 base pairs at a time and is non-overlapping, degenerate, and unambiguous. The fact that the genetic code is non-overlapping implies that during transcription, separate 3 bases or codons are continuous read without "commas". The fact that the genetic code is degenerate also signifies that multiple codons can code for the same amino acid, but more than one amino acid cannot code for one codon; furthermore, since it only codes for a specific amino acid, there is an indication that the genetic code is not ambiguous and is highly specific.
phenomenonA The genetic code is the Rosetta stone that translates between mRNA and proteins, 3 bases at a time.
phenomenonA[comment] I find it fascinating how complex this molecule of DNA is especially regarding it's "simplistic" make-up. I personally don't believe the double helical structure is simple because of the amount of coiling and compaction required to fit DNA that is larger than the organism itself inside a microscopic nucleus. I also find it interesting that one codon can produce amino acids and structural proteins with a few intermediates. Furthermore, I find it fascinating that the DNA can detect environmental changes which can lead to a fluctuation in protein production to accommodate for that change in environmental conditions.
phenomenonB Transcription in eukaryotes differs in fundamental ways from transcription in prokaryotes.
phenomenonB[comment] I am just fascinated at the level of detail that goes through the process of transcription especially since the speed and accuracy rate are low and high, respectively. I personally believe that both prokaryotes and eukaryotes have their own complex mechanisms, but certain issues that arise in eukaryotes don't necessarily arise in prokaryotes thus adding a higher level of understanding of previous concepts which fascinates me.
groupTime456 2544.26

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] This promoter region is essentially an area that can inform the proteins and other crucial substances in transcription where to start. This promoter region in prokaryotes is highly similar to the promoter region in eukaryotes; for instance, the Pribnow Box found in prokaryotes is an AT rich region like the TATA box in eukaryotes. A +1 transcription site is found right next to the promoter (immediately downstream to the promoter) which is where transcription actually initiates. Furthermore, certain certain protein complexes such as suppressors and enhancers can also regulate the transcription rate ny binding upstream to the promoter region; these fluctuations are caused by the change in environmental conditions that send a signal for these suppressors or enhancers.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] A major difference between prokaryotic and eukaryotic transcription is the location of the transcription process. In prokaryotes transcription occurs in the cytoplasm and can occur simultaneously with translation; whereas, transcription in eukaryotes occurs in the nucleus thus not allowing simultaneous transcription and translation processes to occur. Another difference can be noted in the initiation of the transcription process itself, prokaryotes require a core enzyme composed of multiple constant subunits a specific variable subunit called sigma to form a holoenzyme. The sigma subunit allows attachment to the promoter region and leaves after a few base pairs are added this leaving the core enzyme to continue and complete the process of transcription. In eukaryotes, however, RNA polymerase binds to the promoter only after TFIID and other TBP such as TFII H,E,F,A, and B bind to the promoter region. This process is complex since TFIID and TFIIA remain at the promoter site while TFIIH, TFIIB, and TFIIE leave as RNA Polymerase II and TFIIF continue to synthesize the mRNA strand. Termination process also has some variances since eukaryotes have a 3' poly-A tail that prokaryotes do not have.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] The genetic code is a sequence of 3 base pairs and is used to determine the specific amino acid corresponding to the codon sequence given. The genetic code is known to be non-overlapping, comma-less, degenerate, unambiguous, colinear (sequence of codons in a gene is colinear), and is nearly univeral. Due to these characteristics described above and its ability to translate nucleotides into amino acids or "change languages" it can be classified as the initial and inherent Rosetta Stone.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] The Central Dogma states that DNA creates RNA which creates protein via the processes of transcription and translation, respectively. Transcription is the process by which a complementary ribonucleotides strand can be composed in a 5' -> 3' direction from a template strand of the DNA strand that runs in the 3'->5' direction also known as the antisense strand. Transcription can be divided into three divisions or categories in both prokaryotes and eukaryotes-- initiation, elongation, and termination. In prokaryotic initiation a holoenzyme is required to copy the mRNA strand whereas in eukaryotic initiation a DNA polymerase and a few proteins are required. The elongation step refers to the continuous addition of base pairs after the start codon. Finally, the termination step indicates the ending of mRNA ribonucleotides and processing which has certain variances between prokaryotes and eukaryotes. In eukaryotes, the mRNA strand has to have a 5' methylguanosine cap and a 3' poly A tail to prevent degradation by floating nucleases of the newly synthesized strand as it exits the nucleus and into the cytoplasm.

explainConcepts[SQ001] The promoter is a region upstream from the actual gene that signals to the polymerases and transcription factors where to start transcription.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Because of evolutionary divergences that resulted in structural differences in the DNA itself, some elements of transcription are quite different in eukaryotes in comparison to prokaryotes. Transcription occurs in the nucleus, away from all of the ribosomes in eukaryotes. DNA must be uncoiled from nucleosomes in order for transcription to occur in eukaryotes. Gene regulation is more complex in eukaryotes, with promoters, enhancers, silencers, transcription factors, and other proteins play regulatory roles. Because the mRNA must travel outside of the nucleus for translation to occur in eukaryotes, it must undergo some processing in order to safely leave the nucleus without degrading.
explainConcepts[SQ003] The genetic code is the great translator that converts nucleotide-sequenced information into amnio acid-sequenced information. More succinctly, this means that it translates mRNA structures into protein structures. The genetic code is written linearly, with “words” composed of mRNA triplets (or codons) that match up with corresponding amino acids.
phenomenonA The genetic code is the Rosetta stone that translates between mRNA and proteins, 3 bases at a time.

phenomenonB Transcription in eukaryotes differs in fundamental ways from transcription in prokaryotes.
phenomenonB[comment] Because eukaryotes have nucleosomes and prokaryotes do not, eukaryotic transcription requires that the chromatin be unwound from the nucleosome before transcription can occur.

knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand that the genetic code is a CRUCIAL aspect of life as we know it. Without the genetic code, there would be no way to consistently convert specific genes into equally specific proteins. I also understand that the genetic code is unambiguous, meaning that each mRNA codon corresponds to only one amino acid. This ensures precision in the translation process and in the central dogma as a whole. However, a single amino acid can be encoded with multiple codons. I understand that the main point at which the genetic code comes into practice is at the A and E sites in the ribosome. As mRNA is fed through the ribosome, tRNA molecules bring amino acids to the A site. At this point, the codon on the mRNA is matched with a complementary codon on the tRNA, as determined by the genetic code. Connected by the attraction between the two complementary codons, the mRNA and tRNA then move to the E site, where the amino acid is affixed to the polypeptide chain.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I understand that the central dogma of biology is that DNA is converted into RNA through transcription and then RNA is converted into proteins through translation. Therefore, transcription is the first step in the central dogma of biology. It is also accordingly a crucial step that requires precision.

knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I understand that transcription in eukaryotes differed from prokaryotic transcription in several ways. Transcription in eukaryotes occurs in the nucleus under the direction of 3 separate forms of RNA polymerase. Prokaryotic transcription does not occur in the nucleus because prokaryotes lack a nucleus. In prokaryotic transcription the RNA transcript is free to associate with ribosomes prior to the completion of transcription. Initiation of transcription of eukaryotic genes requires the compact chromatin fiber to be uncoiled and the DNA to be made accessible to the RNA polymerase and other regulatory proteins. Eukaryotic RNA polymerases rely on transcription factors to scan and bind to DNA. Alteration of the primary RNA transcript to produce mature eukaryotic mRNA involves many complex stages referred to as "processing" where prokaryotic doesn't.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand that the genetic code is by which DNA stores the genetic information consisting of codons of 3 nucleotides. The functional segments of DNA which doe for the transfer of genetic information are called genes. The genetic code is a set of rules by which information encoded within genetic material (DNA or mRNA) is translated to proteins by living cells. Biological decoding is accomplished by the ribosome which links amino acids in order specified by mRNA using tRNA molecules to carry amino acids and to read the mRNA 3 nucleotides at a time.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I understand that transcription is the first step in the central dogma coming before translation. Transcription is the transfer of genetic information from DNA by the synthesis of a complementary RNA molecule using one strand of the DNA as a template. Translation is the derivation of the amino acid sequence of a polypeptide from the base sequence of an mRNA molecule in association with a ribosome and tRNAs. In order for translation to occur, transcription must happen to give the mRNA code to make the specific protein.

explainConcepts[SQ002] Transcription in eukaryotes is located in the nucleus, consists of transcription factors, chromatin remodeling, enhancers and silencers influence the rate at which transcription occurs, and RNA processing after transcription is unique to eukaryotes.
explainConcepts[SQ003] DNA is transcribed into RNA which is then read three bases at a time, known as a codon, by a ribosome, and each codon calls for a single amino acid addition to the growing peptide chain. Experiments confirmed that the codons were three base pairs in length by showing that three deletions or three additions were required to restore initial reading frame.
phenomenonA The genetic code is the Rosetta stone that translates between mRNA and proteins, 3 bases at a time.
phenomenonA[comment] Because DNA and amino acid sequences are colinear, it is possible, within a few bases, due to the degeneracy and wobble that lies within the last base of each codon, to determine the RNA sequences from an amino acid sequence, and from the RNA sequence the DNA sequence. This has been extremely important in experiments to learn more about DNA, RNA, and the products.
phenomenonB Transcription is regulated by the promoter.
phenomenonB[comment] Mutations in promoters often result in under-transcribed genes, resulting in fewer gene products. Few gene products can result in an abnormal phenotype, and possible disease or disorder. Therefor the promoter is a very important piece of DNA. There are proteins that can bind to the promoter to enhance or reduce transcription by preventing the binding of transcription factors or sigma factors and therefor RNA polymerases.

explainConcepts[SQ001] Promoters are regions of DNA that initiate the transcription of a particular gene. RNA polymerase must bind to the promoter before it can begin transcribing the DNA into mRNA.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Unlike prokaryotes, transcription occurs within the nucleus, which means mRNA must leave the nucleus in order for it to be translated. Additionally, eukaryotic DNA is arranged into chromatin, which must uncoil and move nucleosomes in order for DNA to be accessible to RNA polymerase. Also, eukaryotic RNA polymerases utilize transcription factors to scan and bind DNA.
explainConcepts[SQ003] A mechanism is necessary for translation that changes the language from nucleotides to amino acids; the genetic code functions as this "Rosetta stone." Three ribonucleotide letters (a triplet codon) of mRNA codes for an amino acid, or start or stop signal, which initiate or terminate translation. The genetic code is nearly universal, in that its coding dictionary is used by both eukaryotes, prokaryotes, archaea, and viruses.
phenomenonA The genetic code is the Rosetta stone that translates between mRNA and proteins, 3 bases at a time.

phenomenonB The genetic code is the Rosetta stone that translates between mRNA and proteins, 3 bases at a time.
phenomenonB[comment] Crick also proposed the Wobble Hypothesis, that the first two ribonucleotides of triplet codes are usually more critical than the third.

groupTime455 106.11

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Transcription of DNA by RNA polymerase is accomplished with the help of a promoter region in the DNA. This promoter region, which differs between prokaryotes and eukaryotes, usually consists of a TATA box in addition to other promoters. These promoters allow RNA polymerase to find the correct spot on DNA to start reading.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Transcription in eukaryotes, as is the trend, is more complicated than transcription in prokaryotes. Chiefly, it is the differences in DNA between the domains that causes these fundamental differences in transcription. For instance, eukaryotic RNA is transcribed within the nucleus and is then sent through the nuclear membrane, while prokaryotes have no nucleus. Also, eukaryotic DNA is organized into chromatin which must be uncoiled for RNA polymerase to read it—prokaryotes don't have this problem. Eukaryotic transcription requires certain transcription factors, enhancers, and silencers, while prokaryotes have none of these.
explainConcepts[SQ003] The genetic code is read in sets of three bases at a time. These sets are termed codons, and these codons are used during translation to signal the addition of amino acids. Each codon codes for one amino acid, but the code is degenerate because a single amino acid may be coded for by different codons. The anticodons of tRNA "read" the codons of mRNA in the ribosome by bonding to the complementary codons. This produces a collinear chain of amino acids.
phenomenonA Transcription in eukaryotes differs in fundamental ways from transcription in prokaryotes.
phenomenonA[comment] Differences in transcription between prokaryotes and eukaryotes characterize the greater complexity of eukaryotes.
phenomenonB The genetic code is the Rosetta stone that translates between mRNA and proteins, 3 bases at a time.
phenomenonB[comment] This phenomenon gave us the understanding to successfully sequence the human genome.
groupTime456 2637.17

groupTime455 17.38

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] A promoter is essential for transcription to be able to take place. In prokaryotes, there are specific DNA sequences called prommoters which the RNA polymerase sigma subunit recognizes and binds to in order to begin transcription. These are known as consensus sequences and are repeating. In eukaryotes, there are multiple promoters needed to begin transcription. The first, the core promoter, determines where RNAP II binds to the DNA and begins transcription. There are also regions called the proximal-promoter elements, enhancers, and silencers that influence the efficiency or the rate of transcription initiation.
explainConcepts[SQ002] In eukaryotes, transcription is far more complex than in prokaryotes. Eukaryotes have a lot more genetic information that must be transcribed into mRNA in the transcription process. In eukaryotes it occurs in the nucleus, while in prokaryotes it is in the cytoplasm. In addition, transcription in eukaryotes cannot take place until the densely coiled chromatin undergoes chromatin remodeling and is accessible by RNA polymerase. There is also more regulation in eukaryotes, as there is more interaction between cis-acting DNA sequences and trans-acting protein factors; and there are silencers and enhancers that also regulate transcription speeds. Finally, RNA processing takes place in eukaryotes where the RNA transcript undergoes changes before it is ready to be translated.
explainConcepts[SQ003] The mRNA sequence consists of triplet sequences called codons that each code for a specific amino acid. The genetic code is degenerate, commaless, nonoverlapping, and unambiguous. Each codon translates to one amino acid which join to form proteins. The genetic code is universal, with few exceptions, among species. In addition, the code contains one start codon and three stop codons, with the stop codons not actually coding for a specific amino acid but instead the end of a sequence.
phenomenonA The genetic code is the Rosetta stone that translates between mRNA and proteins, 3 bases at a time.
phenomenonA[comment] The genetic code found in mRNA helps explain the central dogma of Biology that DNA leads to mRNA which leads to proteins. The mRNA is known to arise from DNA and this mRNA is know to yield amino acids thanks to its code. Without the code no amino acids or proteins could be produced.
phenomenonB Transcription in eukaryotes differs in fundamental ways from transcription in prokaryotes.
phenomenonB[comment] The key differences in transcription between eukaryotes and prokaryotes help to explain how eukaryotes are able to process their complex DNA. Thanks to the differences, and increased regulation, transcription can be successful in eukaryotes like it is in prokaryotes. One specific difference is RNA splicing, which allows eukaryotes to cut own pieces of mRNA not necessary to produce the proteins needed during posttranscription modifications.

phenomenonB Transcription in eukaryotes differs in fundamental ways from transcription in prokaryotes.
phenomenonB[comment] Prokaryotes lack a nucleus so they perform transcription in the cytoplasm. Ribosomes also exist in the cytoplasm. This allows simultaneous transcription/translation. As soon as the DNA in encoded into mRNA, it moves into ribsomomes so that the mRNA is being read at the same time bases are being added further down the strand.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Transcription is the first step in the central dogma of biology. This process is regulated by many factors, one of which include the promoter region.The promoter region consists of a sequence of specific nucleotides that help certain transcription factors bind RNA polymerase to the strand to be copied into mRNA. Eukaryotic and prokaryotic organisms have differences in how transcription works, which includes different promoters.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Unlike prokaryotic transcription and translation both occurring in the cytosol, eukaryotic transcription occurs in the nucleus then travels to the cytosol for translation. In prokaryotes, the promoter region allows the attachment of the holoenzyme. The holoenzyme is made up of a core enzyme and a gene-specific sigma subunit. This RNA polymerase is able to run until either a hairpin is formed or a rho protein causes the termination of transcription. In eukaryotes, the promoter region is also called the TATA box. The TATA-binding protein aids transcription factors bind RNA polymerase to the TATA box, thus initiating transcription. However, before the eukaryotic DNA can start transcription, it undergoes chromatin remodeling. Unlike prokaryotes, eukaryotes also undergo heavy post-transcriptional modifications before translation can occur, which include: the addition of a 5' 7-Methylguanosine cap and a 3' Poly-A tail, intron excision and exon splicing.
explainConcepts[SQ003] The genetic code is conserved across the majority of organisms. Because of its degenerate qualities and unambiguousness, the genetic code provides the mechanism by which part of the central dogma is achieved. Many proteins are gene products, located in the nuclear genome. In order to create these products, the DNA is transcribed into an intermediary-messenger RNA.
phenomenonA Transcription in eukaryotes differs in fundamental ways from transcription in prokaryotes.
phenomenonA[comment] I am particularly interested the pre-initiation stage of transcription in eukaryotes. Before RNA polymerase can attach to DNA, it must first be held open by many transcription factors, which include enhancers and silencers. Studying the regulation of these transcriptional factors is key to further understanding epigenetics and its underlying mechanisms.
phenomenonB The genetic code is the Rosetta stone that translates between mRNA and proteins, 3 bases at a time.
phenomenonB[comment] The development and application of CRISPR, a gene-modification tool, has exploded in recent years. The CRISPR technology has the ability to splice and repair a manually targeted gene with high precision. It has significant implications towards the improvement of human gene therapy. However, there are many bioethical questions raised with the potential power to control gene regulation at such high degrees. Currently, there are many ethical concerns regarding designer babies and transhumanism.

knowlegeBasis[SQ002] Eukaryotes have to undergo chromatin remodeling before multiple transcription factors may detect the TATA box and initiate the binding of RNA polymerase. Prokaryotes don't require extensive remodeling or nearly as many transcriptional factors to initiate transcription. Prokaryotic transcription and translation both in the cytosol. Eukaryotic transcription occurs separately in the nucleus, thus is it a delayed process getting from transcription to translation. However, transcription and translation is nearly simultaneous in prokaryotes. Eukaryotes also have many post-transcriptional modifications, which include the addition of a 5' 7-methyl-guanosine cap and a 3' poly-A tail. All of this occurs before the mRNA is transferred to the cytosol for translation by the ribosome.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand that the genetic code consists of many codons, each of which are comprised of three bases. The genetic code is unambiguous and degenerate, which allows the production of a wide variety of proteins from only ~20 amino acids.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I know that transcription is a complex process which, from DNA, produces an intermediary messenger RNA before it begins translation. In eukaryotes, the mRNA must be further modified after transcription before translation can begin. Modifications include polyadenylation, capping, and splicing.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] In order for transcription to start, either the sigma factor in prokaryotes or the general transcription factors in eukaryotes must bind to a sequence called a promoter. Typically the sequence consists of the TATA box and is located upstream of the gene that will be transcribed. Transcription cannot occur without a promoter sequence as there would be no place to RNA polymerase to bind.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Transcription in eukaryotes is different than in prokaryotes. First, the general transcription factors and not the sigma factor bind to the promoter region in eukaryotes. Second, transcription and translation occur separately and indifferent locations as opposed to the same time in prokaryotes. Next, eukaryotes have histone proteins which have to be removed before transcription can occur. After transcription, the mRNA produced in prokaryotes does not need to be processed before translating, but in eukaryotes, the introns must be removed, a poly A tail needs to be added, and the 5’ cap.
explainConcepts[SQ003] The genetic code consists of ribonucleotide bases. It is converted to amino acids via translation and tRNAs which bring in amino acids and are linked together in peptide bonds. The amino acids then form polypeptides and many polypeptides linked together form proteins. In this way the genetic code found in three bases in mRNA triggers the tRNA to insert a particular amino acid into the growing nucleotide chain, thus forming a protein.
phenomenonA Transcription in eukaryotes differs in fundamental ways from transcription in prokaryotes.
phenomenonA[comment] Eukaryotes and prokaryotes have many differences. The differences found in transcription in bacteria are also observed in the mitochondria and the chloroplast DNA. This is consistent with the Endosymbiotic theory.
phenomenonB Transcription is regulated by the promoter.
phenomenonB[comment] Transcription is regulated by many different factors, but the promoter plays a key role in regulation. This can also be seen in mutations. If a mutation occurs in the promoter sequence, this would inhibit transcription and not allow DNA to be converted to mRNA.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] The promoter is the section of DNA that initiates the transcription process, which involves the DNA strand being duplicated and transcribed into mRNA, which is then translated into proteins. Furthermore, the promoter region of DNA is located near the start sites of genes, and they are hundreds of base pairs long. Promoters also work with other transcription factors, such as silencers and enhancers, to control the rate of transcription that occurs within a gene.
explainConcepts[SQ002] In eukaryotes, transcription occurs in the nucleus of the cell; in prokaryotes, the transcription process occurs within the cytoplasm of the cell. In prokaryotes, only a single RNA polymerase is involved in the transcription process, but three RNA polymerases are involved in eukaryotic transcription. In prokaryotes, initiation factors are not required for transcription, but initiation factors are necessary for the start of transcription in eukaryotes.
explainConcepts[SQ003] The genetic code is the set of regulations, involving three base pairs at a time, that encodes for genetic information being translated into amino acid sequences. This process is accomplished by the ribosome, which links amino acids in a particular order. This process is highly similar among all organisms.
phenomenonA The genetic code is the Rosetta stone that translates between mRNA and proteins, 3 bases at a time.
phenomenonA[comment] The genetic code allows researchers to determine where transcription begins and ends through stop codons in the amino acid sequences.
phenomenonB Transcription is regulated by the promoter.
phenomenonB[comment] Silencers or enhancers can be paired with the promoter to regulate the rate of transcription within an organism to keep the genes from mutating and altering the phenotype of the organism.

explainConcepts[SQ001] a promoter is a region of DNA that initiates transcription of a particular gene. Promoters are located near the transcription start sites of genes, on the same strand and upstream on the DNA (towards the 5' region of the sense strand). In bacteria, the promoter contains two short sequence elements approximately -10 and -35 nucleotides upstream from the transcription start site.
explainConcepts[SQ002] in eukaryotes transcription takes place in the nucleus and translation takes place in the cytoplasm. in prokaryotes transcription takes place in the a more spatially compacted place.
explainConcepts[SQ003] The genetic code is the set of rules by which information encoded within genetic material (DNA or mRNA sequences) is translated into proteins by living cells. Biological decoding is accomplished by the ribosome, which links amino acids in an order specified by mRNA, using transfer RNA (tRNA) molecules to carry amino acids and to read the mRNA three nucleotides at a time.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Promoters are located at the 3' end of the template strand's structural genes. In prokaryotes it is the site where RNA polymerase and specific sigma factor bind to begin transcription of the operon (the process is more complicated in eukaryotes). The operon can be regulated in many ways. For example, the lacZYA promoter is followed by one site where the tetrameric repressor LacI binds and forms a complex preventing RNA pol from transcribing the gene.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Transcription in eukaryotes is more complicated than in prokaryotes. Transcription can be immediately followed by translation in prokaryotes due to the lack of a membrane bound nucleus. In eukaryotes, transcription occurs within the nucleus and the mRNA must be delivered to the cytoplasm in order to the translated by the larger eukaryotic ribosomes.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Every three nucleotides of mRNA is a codon. Each codon codes for a single amino acid which is assembled into a polypeptide chain by the ribosome. Each individual amino acid is carried throughout the cell by transfer RNA (tRNA).
phenomenonA Transcription in eukaryotes differs in fundamental ways from transcription in prokaryotes.
phenomenonA[comment] Attenuation of the tryptophan operon relies on the ability to transcribe and translate at the same time. Transcription halts if a terminating stem loop forms out of the mRNA and comes in contact with the polymerase synthesizing the strand. When tryptophan levels are low the ribosome stalls on two adjacent trp codons, preventing the stem loop from forming and thus allowing for transcription.
phenomenonB Transcription in eukaryotes differs in fundamental ways from transcription in prokaryotes.
phenomenonB[comment] Transcription in some archaea differs than that of prokaryotes and eukaryotes. These extremophiles contain a topoisomerase similar to gyrase, except that it overwinds the DNA instead of unwinding it. This prevents the DNA from melting at such high temperatures.

Some evolutionary biologists, propose that evolution in promoter or regulatory regions may be more important than changes in coding sequences over such time frames.
phenomenonB Transcription in eukaryotes differs in fundamental ways from transcription in prokaryotes.
phenomenonB[comment] Eukaryotic gene regulation is more complex than prokaryotic gene regulation. The upstream regulatory regions of eukaryotic genes have binding sites for multiple transcription factors, both positive regulators and negative regulators, that work in combination to determine the level of transcription.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Transcription is the first part of the central dogma that describes how DNA leads to the production of proteins. DNA is transcribed into RNA which is the translated to amino acids that make up proteins. Transcription begins when RNA polymerase binds to the promoter region. In bacteria, there are two promoter regions. Therefore, the importance of the promoter region is that it shows where transcription begins.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Transcription in eukaryotes is different from prokaryotes in several ways. First, eukaryotes have a nuclear membrane that the mRNA must leave the nucleus to be translated in the ribosome. Also, eukaryotes are much more complex upstream of the coding sequence. Eukaryotes have a TATA box as well as a CAAT box. The absence of a sigma factor is another difference from prokaryotes. Finally, in eukaryotes a single gene is copied and in prokaryotes multiple genes can be a part of the same transcript.
explainConcepts[SQ003] The genetic code is the Rosetta Stone between mRNA and proteins because the Rosetta Stone was the key to the deciphering of languages in the same way that the genetic code allows mRNA bases to be translated into proteins. The study of frameshift mutations through insertion and deletions allowed for the discovery of the bases being read 3 at a time.
phenomenonA Transcription in eukaryotes differs in fundamental ways from transcription in prokaryotes.
phenomenonA[comment] The fact that transcription differs so fundamentally in eukaryotes from transcription in prokaryotes is interesting because its taught that eukaryotic cells arose from prokaryotic ones so one would think that their genetic material became proteins in more similar fashion. Therefore, the differences in eukaryotic and prokaryotic transcription is related to evolution which is an interesting biological phenomenon.
phenomenonB Transcription is regulated by the promoter.
phenomenonB[comment] Transcription being regulated by the promoter is interesting to me personally because it is critical to the production of proteins which are essential to all of the functions of an organism.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] The promoter is the region of DNA that initiates transcription of a particular gene. Promoters are located near the transcription start sites on the same strand and upstream on DNA. Transcriptional regulation is the means by which a cell regulates the conversion of DNA to RNA.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Transcription in eukaryotes occurs within the nucleus under the direction of three separate forms of RNA polymerase. Unlike the prokaryote process, in eukaryotes the RNA transcript is not free to associate with ribosomes prior to the completion of transcription. For the mRNA to be translated, it must move out of the nucleus into the cytoplasm. Initiation of transcription of eukaryotic genes requires the compact chromatin fiber, characterized by nucleosome coiling, to be uncoiled and the DNA to be made accessible to RNA polymerase and other regulatory proteins.
explainConcepts[SQ003] The genetic code is the set of rules by which the information encoded within genetic material is translated into proteins by living cells. Amino acids are in an order specified by mRNA using tRNA to carry amino acids and read the mRNA 3 at a time. Each set of three nucleotides has a corresponding protein depending on the combination of letters.
phenomenonA The genetic code is the Rosetta stone that translates between mRNA and proteins, 3 bases at a time.
phenomenonA[comment] This is important when looking at mutations and figuring out where things might have gone wrong. The genetic code is extremely important in organisms because this is the components that make it up essentially and being able to translate the mRNA into proteins is vital and knowing how this happens, the process, etc. will help to solve diseases and prevent mutations from occurring.
phenomenonB Transcription in eukaryotes differs in fundamental ways from transcription in prokaryotes.
phenomenonB[comment] Eukaryotes and prokaryotes are very different as we already know. Eukaryotes are much more complex and this stays true with their transcription process. It is important to realize that prokaryotes and eukaryotes if something goes wrong with transcription, it will affect these organisms differently. For instance if something goes wrong with transcription in a eukaryote it is much more detrimental than it would be for a prokaryote seeing that eukaryotes are much more complex and have many more processes and places for things to go wrong.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Some of these are expressed in all cells all the time. These so-called housekeeping genes are responsible for the routine metabolic functions (e.g. respiration) common to all cells. Some are expressed as a cell enters a particular pathway of differentiation. Some are expressed all the time in only those cells that have differentiated in a particular way. For example, a plasma cell expresses continuously the genes for the antibody it synthesizes. Some are expressed only as conditions around and in the cell change. For example, the arrival of a hormone may turn on (or off) certain genes in that cell.
explainConcepts[SQ002] In bacteria, all transcription is performed by a single type of RNA polymerase. This polymerase contains four catalytic subunits and a single regulatory subunit known as sigma (s). Interestingly, several distinct sigma factors have been identified, and each of these oversees transcription of a unique set of genes. Sigma factors are thus discriminatory, as each binds a distinct set of promoter sequences.
explainConcepts[SQ003] The genetic code consists of 64 triplets of nucleotides. These triplets are called codons.With three exceptions, each codon encodes for one of the 20 amino acids used in the synthesis of proteins. That produces some redundancy in the code: most of the amino acids being encoded by more than one codon.
phenomenonA Transcription in eukaryotes differs in fundamental ways from transcription in prokaryotes.
phenomenonA[comment] That is why Eukaryotes are more complicated and are animals while, prokaryotes are less complicated bacteria cells that you see in public bathrooms
phenomenonB Transcription is regulated by the promoter.
phenomenonB[comment] In DNA, regulation of gene expression normally happens at the level of RNA biosynthesis (transcription), and is accomplished through the sequence-specific binding of proteins (transcription factors) that activate or inhibit transcription.
groupTime456 1254.35

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] In RNA, regulation may occur at the level of protein biosynthesis (translation), RNA cleavage, RNA splicing, or transcriptional termination. Regulatory sequences are frequently associated with messenger RNA (mRNA) molecules, where they are used to control mRNA biogenesis or translation.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] Centrosome: The centrosome, or MICROTUBULE ORGANIZING CENTER (MTOC), is an area in the cell where microtubules are produced. Plant and animal cell centrosomes play similar roles in cell division, and both include collections of microtubules, but the plant cell centrosome is simpler and does not have centrioles.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] The genetic code is the set of rules by which information encoded within genetic material (DNA or mRNA sequences) is translated into proteins by living cells. Biological decoding is accomplished by the ribosome, which links amino acids in an order specified by mRNA, using transfer RNA (tRNA) molecules to carry amino acids and to read the mRNA three nucleotides at a time. The genetic code is highly similar among all organisms and can be expressed in a simple table with 64 entries.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] But, did you ever wonder how a particular sequence of the nucleotides, called A, C, G and T, can lead to noticeable physical characteristics? The central dogma of biology describes just that. It provides the basic framework for how genetic information flows from a DNA sequence to a protein product inside cells. This process of genetic information flowing from DNA to RNA to protein is called gene expression.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Transcription is regulated by the presence of a promoter region. Transcription promoter regions in prokaryotes are RNA-coding sequences that are found upstream of transcription start site in the 5' region. There are strong and weak promoters. Strong promoters are present on very transcriptionally active DNA molecules. These promoter regions are recognized by RNA polymerase theta molecules. RNA polymerase scans the DNA until it comes into contact with one of these promoter regions where it binds to the DNA. Once RNA polymerase binds, the DNA helix is locally unwound so that it can be transcribed by the enzyme. Transcription actually begins at the transcription start site. Without these promoter regions, RNA polymerase would not know where to bind the DNA and begin transcription.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Transcription between eukaryotes and prokaryotes differs in very fundamental ways. First, transcription in eukaryotes occurs within the nucleus. Three different RNA polymerase forms are involved with this transcription. Unlike in prokaryotes, eukaryotic RNA transcripts cannot associate with ribosomes before transcription is completed. Also, eukaryotic chromatin fibers have to uncoil in order for the DNA to be accessible to RNA polymerase for transcription. Prokaryotic DNA doesn’t not form chromatin. Also, eukaryotic transcription produces RNA that has to be processed before it can leave the nucleus and begin translation. This includes, addition of a 5’cap and poly a tail and splicing.
explainConcepts[SQ003] The genetic code is analogous to the Rosetta stone for gene expression. The genetic code is made up of the four nucleotide bases, adenine, thymine, cytosine, and guanine, found in DNA molecules. These DNA nucleotides are transcribed into RNA nucleotides, which are the same minus the exception of uracil for thymine. RNA nucleotides are arranged into groups of three called codons. During translation, each codon can code for a single amino acid, which can be subsequently linked together via phosphodiester bonds. Therefore the genetic code found in DNA that is transcribed into mRNA molecules which are then translated into proteins concluding the central dogma.
phenomenonA The genetic code is the Rosetta stone that translates between mRNA and proteins, 3 bases at a time.
phenomenonA[comment] The information stored in DNA can be transcribed into RNA and subsequently translated in proteins. This idea is very important biologically because it provides the basis for the central dogma and for gene expression. Information stored in DNA has the capability to code for a wide variety of proteins with a wide variety of functions that allow complex life as we know it to exist.
phenomenonB Transcription is regulated by the promoter.
phenomenonB[comment] Without promoter regions, RNA polymerase would not know where to bind to DNA to begin transcription. This is biologically important because many times certain genes are needed to be expressed, but if no promoter region existed to signal to the RNA polymerase enzyme where it needed to bind the gene product would never be produced.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] For transcription to take place RNA polymerase must attach to the DNA near a gene. Promoters contain specific DNA sequences that provide a secure initial binding site for RNA polymerase and for transcription factors that recruit RNA polymerase. The transcription factors have specific activator or repressor sequences of corresponding nucleotides that attach to specific promoters and regulate gene expression.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Transcription takes place in the nucleus of eukaryotes, but in the cytoplasm of prokaryotes. Eukaryotes must allow their chromatin to uncoil and allow RNA polymerase to bind as well as shift nucleosomes, while prokaryotes do not. Prokaryotes do not need proteins or transcription factors for initiation, while eukaryotes utilize many types of these. Also, prokaryotes only use one RNA polymerase of 5 nucleotides to produce the 3 types of RNA, while eukaryotes use various types of RNA polymerases of 10-15 nucleotides.
explainConcepts[SQ003] The genetic code is the sequence of nucleotides transcribed from DNA to mRNA separated into codons which are translated by tRNA which transports different amino acids that form a polypeptide which can be linked to form proteins.
phenomenonA The genetic code is the Rosetta stone that translates between mRNA and proteins, 3 bases at a time.
phenomenonA[comment] The universality of the genetic code is so incredible. It is what allows us to make comparisons and findings across species and kingdoms. The discovery of the structure of DNA and the genetic code is what has allowed us to understand many metabolic processes and pathways, and come up with new treatments for hereditary diseases. Gene therapy and genetic testing both pre- and -post birth have changed the way we live and decisions we can make.
phenomenonB Transcription in eukaryotes differs in fundamental ways from transcription in prokaryotes.
phenomenonB[comment] This common theme of biology, the differences between prokaryotes and eukaryotes, is simply reiterated throughout the process of DNA replication as well as protein production. Its typical features are still present as well, with eukaryotic processes being more complex and with more components. This is required simply because of the size of the organisms' genomes (~10^6 vs. ~10^9) and the diversity of function in eukaryotes (organelles, cell types, etc.).

groupTime455 87.9

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] A promoter is a sequence of nucleotide bases on the gene that serve as a signal and binding site for RNA polymerase. Without a promoter region, RNA polymerase would not be able to recognize the gene to be transcribed. The promoter sequence, or TATA box, is upstream of the gene to be transcribed. Mutations in the promoter sequence causes an inability of RNA polymerase to function and a disruption of the central dogma.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Eukaryotes have a linear DNA and prokaryotes have a circular one. This can cause a problem at the end of the eukaryotic strand during replication, which is solved by the addition of telomerases. Eukaryotic replication is 25 times slower than prokaryotic replication, but there are multiple replication sites in eukaryotes and only one in prokaryotes. Eukaryotes have histone proteins that clump together and compact sections of DNA to turn them off. Eukaryotes have two different polymerases that copy the leading and lagging strand while prokaryotes only have one. In eukaryotic transcription is initiated by a RNA primer which is converted into DNA. There is only a RNA primer in prokaryotes.
explainConcepts[SQ003] The nucleotide bases that make up mRNA are using open reading frames by ribosomes in the cytoplasm. Amino acid residues are added one at at time to the growing polypeptide chain. The tRNA delivers delivers the specific amino acid according to the anticodon sequence at the opposite end of the tRNA. Three base groupings are called codons, and every combination of the 4 nucleotide bases codes for a specific amino acid or the start (AUG) or stop (UGA, UAA, UGG).
phenomenonA Transcription in eukaryotes differs in fundamental ways from transcription in prokaryotes.
phenomenonA[comment] While transcription in eukaryotes differs from prokaryotes in many ways, they may have a common history. New evidence and theories suggest that RNA may have been the original form of all genetic material, and over time it was mutated into DNA.
phenomenonB Transcription is regulated by the promoter.
phenomenonB[comment] Mutations in the promoter region disrupt the central dogma (DNA to RNA), because the DNA can't be transcribed to begin the pathway to synthesize a protein. Mutations in the promoter sequence have been connected to many diseases like asthma.
