I understand that transcribing RNA from the DNA is the first step in the central dogma of information flow. I understand that the promoter region we covered in class is called the TATA box.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I understand that eukaryotic transcription differs in 5 fundamental ways from prokaryotic transcription. I understand that transcription is much slower in eukaryotes than prokaryotes, but that is made up for by having multiple transcription sites. I understand that eukaryotic DNA is linear (not circular like prokaryotes) and telomerases must be added to the end of the chromosomes to prevent the genetic material from being truncated during replication. I understand that eukaryotes use two different RNA polymerases and prokaryotes only use one. I understand that eukaryotic DNA is packed into nucleosomes, which must be removed in order to transcribe genes. I understand that the RNA primer is converted to DNA in eukaryotes but not in prokaryotes.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand that the genetic code is the Rosetta stone in that there are 3 different "languages" or versions of the same code that result from our specific DNA sequences. I understand the central dogma of information flow that first transcribes DNA (first language) to RNA (second language) which is then translated into polypeptide chains (third language) which can then be used to form functioning proteins in the cell. This code is passed by reading 3 base groupings at a time called codons. I understand that ribosomes in the cytoplasm read the mRNA strands by open reading frame, and tRNA carries the appropriate amino acid to the ribosome to add to the growing polypeptide chain. One amino acid can be represented by more than one base grouping.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I understand the central dogma of biology, and I understand that transcription is the first step. I understand that the central dogma has three stages with two processes involved. First, the DNA is transcribed into RNA. Second, RNA is translated by ribosomes in the cytoplasm into polypeptide chains (aka proteins). The central dogmas three stages are DNA to RNA to protein and the two processes are transcription and translation.

groupTime456 813.97

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] Promoters are DNA sequences located in the 5' region adjacent to the transcriptional start site. RNA polymerase and transcription factors bind to the promoter to initiate production of an mRNA transcript. Interactions of proteins at the promoter regulate gene activity by activating or repressing transcription.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] Eukaryotes contain many different promoter elements: TATA box, initiator elements, downstream core promoter element, CAAT box, and the GC box to name a few. Eukaryotes have three types of RNA polymerases, I, II, and III, and prokaryotes only have one type. Eukaryotes form and initiation complex with the various transcription factors that dissociate after initiation is completed. There is no such structure seen in prokaryotes. Another main difference between the two is that transcription and translation occurs simultaneously in prokaryotes and in eukaryotes the RNA is first transcribed in the nucleus and then translated in the cytoplasm.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] The genetic code consists of 64 triplets of nucleotides and these are called codons, they each code for one of the 20 amino acids used in synthesis of proteins.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] During transcription, a DNA sequence is read by RNA polymerase.This produces a complementary, antiparallel RNA strand. Unlike DNA replication, transcription results in an RNA complement that substitutes the RNA uracil in all instances where the DNA thymine would have occurred. Transcription is the first step in gene expression.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] The promoter is located upstream from the transcribed region. It is recognized and the proper enzymes are put into place so that transcription can begin at exactly the correct base.
explainConcepts[SQ002] In prokaryotes, transcription occurs in the cytoplasm. The promoter region recognized by σ70 factor RNA polymerase holoenzyme. Then RNA polymerase initiates RNA synthesis, σ leaves, chain elongation proceeds, proofreading, termination sequence intrinsic (GC) or ρ(C rut) forms hairpin 2° structure. In eukaryotes, RNA polymerase I transcribes 28S,18S,5.8S rRNAs. RNA polymeraase II transcribes mRNAs & snRNAs. RNA polymerase III transcribes tRNAs, 5S rRNA & snRNAs. Transcription depends on general transcription factors. Transcription occurs in the nucleus and the mRNA must be edited before leaving the nucleus to go to the cytoplasm for translation with ribosomes.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Genetic code is linear, codons, unambiguous, degenerate (wobble hypothesis 3rd position), start (AUG=met), stop (UAA, UAG, UGA), commaless, nonoverlapping (Crick 3 +/- restore frame), collinear, universal (exceptions mt wobble), ordered (chemically similar amino acids share middle bases in codons).
phenomenonA The genetic code is the Rosetta stone that translates between mRNA and proteins, 3 bases at a time.
phenomenonA[comment] With few mitochonidrial exceptions, the genetic code is universal. This means the 3 base pairs encode for the same proteins in all living things. This conservation relates to evolution.
phenomenonB Transcription is regulated by the promoter.
phenomenonB[comment] Mutations in the promoter region lead to decreased transcription, which affects protein synthesis and the phenotype of the cell. These mutations can be lethal to fetuses or other developing organisms.

knowlegeBasis[SQ004] The genetic code must be transcribed into a message readable by ribosomes and tRNA anticodons before it can be translated into proteins. Transcription is very important and must be efficient and accurate for life.

explainConcepts[SQ001] Promoters contain DNA sequences that provide an initial binding site for RNA polymerase and for transcription factor proteins that recruit RNA polymerase regulating the transcription fctor
explainConcepts[SQ002] Eukaryotes have positive or negative control close to and also far away from the cell prokaryotes can only demonstrate +/- control in nearby sites. eukaryotes require a mediator complex and prokaryotes utilize the sigma factor as the promotor
explainConcepts[SQ003] Genetic code is transcribed from DNA into mRNA which is then translated into proteins based on 3 subunit codons that code for a specific amino acid, the 20 amino acid sequence is then transformed into protein
phenomenonA The genetic code is the Rosetta stone that translates between mRNA and proteins, 3 bases at a time.
phenomenonA[comment] the basis of all life is coded as DNA that is transcribed and then translated into proteins providing the fundamental building blocks for cells
phenomenonB Transcription is regulated by the promoter.
phenomenonB[comment] transcription must be heavily regulated in order to prevent large numbers of point mutations and deletions that could be lethal to an organism
